trans-unit.source: The Graph API is an OData 3.0 compliant REST API that provides programmatic access to directory objects in Azure Active Directory, such as users, groups, organizational contacts, and applications.
trans-unit.target: The Graph API is an OData 3.0 compliant REST API that provides programmatic access to directory objects in Azure Active Directory, such as users, groups, organizational contacts, and applications.

trans-unit.source: Azure AD Graph API functionality is also available through [Microsoft Graph](https://graph.microsoft.io/), a unified API that also includes APIs from other Microsoft services like Outlook, OneDrive, OneNote, Planner, and Office Graph, all accessed through a single endpoint with a single access token.

trans-unit.source: Organizational contacts represent users that are not in your company directory.
trans-unit.target: Organizational contacts represent users that are not in your company directory.

trans-unit.source: They are mail-enabled entities and typically represent individuals who are external to your company or organization.
trans-unit.target: They are mail-enabled entities and typically represent individuals who are external to your company or organization.

trans-unit.source: Organizational contacts cannot be authenticated using Azure AD, nor can they be assigned licenses.
trans-unit.target: Organizational contacts cannot be authenticated using Azure AD, nor can they be assigned licenses.

trans-unit.source: Organizational contacts can be created in your tenant through syncing with an on-premises directory using Azure AD Connect, or they can be created through one of the Exchange Online management portals or the Exchange Online PowerShell cmdlets.
